# Coding Standards — Starfield Starmap Explorer

## Language & Syntax

- This codebase uses **modern JavaScript (ES6+)**. Use `const`, `let`, arrow functions, `async/await`, template literals, and destructuring freely.
- Do NOT downgrade to `var` or ES5-style code — the original codebase is already ES6+ and mixing would be inconsistent.
- Do not introduce classes, modules, imports, or exports (single-file architecture).

## File Structure

- Everything lives in **one HTML file**.
- CSS is in the `<style>` block. JS is in the `<script>` block. No separate files.
- Do not split the file. Do not add `<link>` or `<script src="">` tags for new dependencies.
- Tailwind CSS and Font Awesome CDN links are already present — use them; don't duplicate them.

## Functions & Naming

- Preserve all existing function names — they may be referenced by event listeners or other functions.
- New functions should follow existing naming style: camelCase, short and descriptive.
- Async functions that use the File System Access API must include a `try/catch` and a graceful fallback.

## State Management

- All exploration, scan, and note state lives in `systemStates{}`.
- Any mutation to `systemStates` must be followed immediately by `saveSystemStates()`.
- `starSystemsData[]` is read-only static data — never mutate it at runtime.
- Pan/zoom state lives in the transform variables on the map container — do not add a parallel copy.

## Save System — Critical Rules

- `saveSystemStates()` writes `systemStates` to `localStorage`. Call it after **every** state mutation.
- `loadSystemStates()` reads from `localStorage`. Called once on boot — do not call it again after user interaction.
- `applyLoadedSaveData(data)` merges a loaded JSON object into `systemStates` and calls `saveSystemStates()`. It does not replace the whole object blindly — preserve any keys not present in the loaded file.
- File System Access API calls must be wrapped in `if (window.showDirectoryPicker)` guards.

## Pan / Zoom — Critical Rules

- `mouseup` / `pointerup` listeners that clear the pan state must be on `document`, not just the map container — otherwise releasing outside the window leaves the map stuck in drag mode.
- The map container cursor must be reset to `grab` after drag ends (remove `grabbing` class).
- Zoom must be bounded — enforce min/max scale to prevent the map disappearing off-screen.

## DOM

- Map points are rendered from `starSystemsData[]`. To update a map point's visual state (explored colour, note icon), update the relevant DOM element directly by `id` or class — do not re-render the whole map.
- The info panel content is replaced on each system click — that is expected behaviour.
- The note modal is a shared singleton — populate it with the current system's data before showing it.

## CSS

- Use existing Tailwind utility classes for layout and spacing.
- Use the existing custom CSS variables and classes (`.mappoint`, `.point1`–`.point4`, `.note-icon`, `.scan-icon`, `.info-panel`) for consistency.
- New map-specific styles go in the `<style>` block, not as inline styles.
- Dark space aesthetic must be preserved: background `#0d1117`, dark surfaces, muted star colours.
- Do not add light backgrounds or bright white UI elements — this is a night-mode-only interface.

## Browser Compatibility

- Target: **Chrome** (primary — required for File System Access API).
- Firefox and Safari: all features except folder-based save/load should work. Document any new API that has limited support.
- No polyfills — if an API isn't available, detect and gracefully degrade (e.g. fall back to download link).

## Error Handling

- Use `try/catch` for all `async` File System API calls and all `JSON.parse` calls.
- Use the existing `showMessageBox(title, message)` for user-facing error messages.
- Do not use `alert()` except for destructive confirmation dialogs (e.g. "Reset all exploration?").
- Silent failures are acceptable for non-critical UI (e.g. minimap, counter animation) but not for save/load.

## Comments

- Add comments only where logic is non-obvious.
- Section headers use `/* === SECTION === */` style.
- Do not add explanatory comments to every line.
